<DOC><DOCNO> AP880521-0067 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-21-88 0651EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Taiwan-Riot 1stLd-Writethru a0513 05-21 0470</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Taiwan-Riot, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0513,0482</SECOND><HEAD>Police Crush Bloody Anti-Government Riots In Taipei</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: To specify farmers' demands, SUB 4th graf, `The fighting ...for farmers.' Picks up 5th graf pvs, `About 3,000 ...</NOTE><BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Thousands of protesters disrupted railtraffic, smashed vehicles and hurled rocks at club-swinging policeduring 18 hours of bloody riots on the streets of Taipei, policeand witnesses said today.   An estimated 200 people were injured during the anti-governmentdemonstrations that were quelled early today. Police said 130protesters were arrested.   Local media described the roving riots as among the worst publicdisturbances in Taiwan since the Nationalist Chinese governmentfled the Communist mainland for this island in 1949.   The fighting began Friday during a demonstration demanding thatthe government provide farmers with insurance and quadruple itsrice purchases.   About 3,000 rock-throwing protesters clashed with police at theLegislative Yuan, Taiwan's highest legislative body, before movingto the headquarters of the governing Nationalist Party.   At a police station, rioters smashed five police vans and setfire a car and a motorcycle, police said.   Riot police used batons and water cannons to disperse most ofthe protesters from the front of the police station. Demonstrationleader Lin Kuo-hwa and 11 other activists were arrested, witnessessaid.   Police chased about 200 remaining protesters throughout thecity, fighting pitched battles in front of government buildings andbusinesses.   The rioters tore out rails at a railroad crossing, disruptingtrain traffic for three hours and smashed phone booths before theywere dispersed, police said.   Police beat demonstrators with clubs and stomped on some whofell to the ground, the liberal Independence Evening Post reportedtoday.   Two policemen, two photographers and four protesters werehospitalized with head injuries, police reported.   Another 60 officers were treated at hospitals and released, saidpolice, who put the total casualties at approximately 200 people.   Taipei Police Deputy Chief Wang Hwa-cheng said among thosearrested were people who ``posed as farmers and incited the crowdin an attempt to disrupt the 40 years of development on thisisland.''   Wang did not elaborate, but authorities said oppositionDemocratic Progressive Party members and students were among thedemonstrators.   Presiding Judge Liu Ching-yi of the Taipei District Court saidmost of the detained protesters were ``non-farmers,'' claiming somemay have been incited by ``communist elements'' who infiltratedfrom the rival Chinese government in Beijing. He also did notelaborate.   Demonstrating farmers had accused the government of ignoringtheir concerns while focusing on industrial development.   They demanded that President Lee Teng-hui, an agriculturaleconomics expert who succeeded the late Chiang Ching-kuo inJanuary, help improve the livelihood of farmers who have been hurtby low prices for farm goods.   Lee urged agricultural officials Friday to help solve farmers'problems.</TEXT></DOC>